<font color="#FF0000">RAPE II</font><br>
<tt>Sat Mar  8 11:47:03 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Wingman and Art<br>
If it wasn't for your handle, Tom, I would have forgotten that you were involved with aircraft.  I tend to forget names, much less Bios.  Has to do with respect, I think, those that don't need to prove something to me, I only need to remember that you were there.  Same-same for you, Art.  Tom's last posting reminded me that you were with Arty.<br><br>
Points of reference-Wingman, not sure of your craft, doesn't matter, they all were life savers, the little loach buzzing over our A.O., trying to draw the bead from Chuck, so that the pilot could say, &quot;Hey, hey, looky, looky around you boys, Chucky baby wants to do you some hurt from that direction!&quot;  The pilots and crews of slicks, dustoffs, cobra gunships, whose job was to take us into the shit, extract us from the shit, and to cover our asses at all times. Spooky, a craft after my own heart, too rare for my taste, with his mini-guns, i.e., peace-makers.  And then there was the lone pilot who had the guts to fly all alone in a joke of a piper cub in Charlie's backyard.  I remember once looking up as he went over, and felt a momentary stab of lonliness for him.<br><br>
Point of reference-Spending three hours stumbling into a massive bunker complex that took us three days to extricate ourselves from. Charlie's mortars and fire and the screams. And the call for arty support by 2-6 from a 175 and 8 incher battery, and the call by 2-6 to finally lay it down on us.  No &quot;adjust fire&quot;, just &quot; fire for effect!&quot;, and the terror as these fell around us, lifting us off the ground, while trees were trying to lay us down and shit flying everywhere, and the amazement by all of us that there were no line ones or KIA's, just some wounded and several bleeding ears and noses.<br><br>
HEY, 2-6, YOU DID GOOD THAT DAY!!  DO YOU REMEMBER, 2-6?  Oh, yeah, I forgot, 2-6, we had to send you up by cable in a metal frame and mesh litter.  Well, you did good, anyway.<br><br>
I had spent thirty years trying to forget.  To a certain degree, I had forgotten much.  Had to ask Terry Crenshaw the name used for the jungle penetrater.  I know we used it, I just don't remember when or how or why.  I don't remember a lot of things, especially names and faces,<br><br>
My point is that it has taken me thirty years to learn that, by forgetting these things, I am playing into the hands of those who want to discredit these experiences for whatever reasons.<br><br>
&gt;No one can deny our experiences.&lt;<br><br>
I agree with most of what you have said above except for this one small line, Arthur.<br><br>
Yes, they can.  They have been trying for these many years. And they had our help in doing so! We had allowed the likes of Nurse Ratchet to do so.  But no more from this one!<br><br>
Hey, Nurse Ratchet!  Come and debate me. Justify your positions and I will do the same.  Come and do verbal battle, the stakes are high; your personal integrity versus mine and my fellow vets.  Come on, Jeffery and Tanker and Gerald Ney are having all the fun!  Let us join in with our own issues!
<p><code>-- docdel@maui.net  (Doc Del) </code><p>


